00:01:07.532 --> 00:01:31.250 align:middle line:90%


00:01:31.250 --> 00:01:34.160 align:middle line:84%
>> If there were a giant map of
the world's great mythologies,

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:37.250 align:middle line:84%
you could throw a dart and
anywhere it lands you find

00:01:37.250 --> 00:01:40.970 align:middle line:84%
a love story, tales woven to
express the heart's deepest

00:01:40.970 --> 00:01:42.060 align:middle line:90%
desire.

00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:44.210 align:middle line:84%
For example, the
ancient Babylonian myth

00:01:44.210 --> 00:01:46.850 align:middle line:84%
of Pyramus and Thisbe,
two young lovers

00:01:46.850 --> 00:01:49.820 align:middle line:84%
doomed by a chance
mistake and bad timing,

00:01:49.820 --> 00:01:53.600 align:middle line:84%
or Echo and Narcissus,
a trail of seductions

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:56.290 align:middle line:84%
that ends with a dagger
through a broken heart--

00:01:56.290 --> 00:01:57.090 align:middle line:90%
just too many.

00:01:57.090 --> 00:02:00.680 align:middle line:84%
So take your pick, there
are multitudes of choices.

00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:02.660 align:middle line:84%
The study of the
mythology of love

00:02:02.660 --> 00:02:04.700 align:middle line:84%
was a favorite of
Joseph Campbell.

00:02:04.700 --> 00:02:06.950 align:middle line:84%
One of his best and
most famous essays

00:02:06.950 --> 00:02:09.650 align:middle line:84%
celebrates this
universal mystery.

00:02:09.650 --> 00:02:11.420 align:middle line:84%
Ask him where he
would like to start,

00:02:11.420 --> 00:02:13.190 align:middle line:84%
as I did during
our conversations

00:02:13.190 --> 00:02:15.930 align:middle line:84%
on the power of myth a
quarter of a century ago,

00:02:15.930 --> 00:02:18.920 align:middle line:84%
and he invariably answered,
in the Middle Ages.

00:02:18.920 --> 00:02:21.770 align:middle line:84%
He relished in stories
of love and courtship

00:02:21.770 --> 00:02:24.680 align:middle line:84%
for the noble and gentle
hearts that managed somehow

00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:27.380 align:middle line:90%
to transcend raw lust.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:29.480 align:middle line:84%
Because those stories
helped to create

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:31.890 align:middle line:84%
a distinctive Western
consciousness,

00:02:31.890 --> 00:02:34.820 align:middle line:84%
in time they would encourage
personal challenges

00:02:34.820 --> 00:02:36.950 align:middle line:84%
to the dogma of
church and state.

00:02:36.950 --> 00:02:39.140 align:middle line:84%
So love, in other
words, as Joe said,

00:02:39.140 --> 00:02:42.880 align:middle line:84%
could lead to revolution,
even against God.

00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:44.830 align:middle line:84%
Our first conversations
took place

00:02:44.830 --> 00:02:48.040 align:middle line:84%
at George Lucas's Skywalker
Ranch in California.

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:50.530 align:middle line:84%
Like a weaver of
fine cloth, Campbell

00:02:50.530 --> 00:02:53.050 align:middle line:84%
spun the tales and
legends of love

00:02:53.050 --> 00:02:55.795 align:middle line:84%
to a marvelous tapestry
of the human psyche.

00:02:55.795 --> 00:03:00.330 align:middle line:90%


00:03:00.330 --> 00:03:02.816 align:middle line:90%
Let's talk about love.

00:03:02.816 --> 00:03:04.980 align:middle line:90%
>> Let's talk about love, fine.

00:03:04.980 --> 00:03:08.460 align:middle line:84%
>> But it's such a vast subject
that in mythology that if I had

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:12.270 align:middle line:84%
come to you and said, let's talk
about love but where should we

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:15.780 align:middle line:84%
begin, what would
your answer have been?

00:03:15.780 --> 00:03:18.420 align:middle line:84%
>> I think my answer would
have been the troubadours

00:03:18.420 --> 00:03:19.690 align:middle line:90%
in the 12th century.

00:03:19.690 --> 00:03:21.960 align:middle line:90%
Let's begin there.

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:23.130 align:middle line:90%
>> Why the troubadours?

00:03:23.130 --> 00:03:25.620 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, because they're the
first ones in the West that

00:03:25.620 --> 00:03:30.570 align:middle line:84%
really considered love in the
sense that we think of it now,

00:03:30.570 --> 00:03:34.050 align:middle line:84%
as a person-to-person
relationship.

00:03:34.050 --> 00:03:36.400 align:middle line:84%
>> You're talking
about romantic love?

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:37.230 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:03:37.230 --> 00:03:42.220 align:middle line:84%
It is the seizure that
comes in recognizing

00:03:42.220 --> 00:03:46.200 align:middle line:84%
as where your soul's
counterpart in the other person,

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:51.180 align:middle line:84%
and that's what the
troubadours stood for,

00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:55.530 align:middle line:84%
and that has become the
ideal in our lives today.

00:03:55.530 --> 00:03:57.510 align:middle line:90%
>> What had it been before that?

00:03:57.510 --> 00:04:01.950 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, the idea
of love as Eros,

00:04:01.950 --> 00:04:07.530 align:middle line:84%
the god who excites
you to sexual desire,

00:04:07.530 --> 00:04:10.430 align:middle line:84%
this is not the
person-to-person thing,

00:04:10.430 --> 00:04:14.610 align:middle line:84%
the falling in love in the way
the troubadours understood it.

00:04:14.610 --> 00:04:21.490 align:middle line:84%
I have a definition for Eros,
the erotic biological urge

00:04:21.490 --> 00:04:25.260 align:middle line:84%
as the zeal of the
organs for each other.

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:29.640 align:middle line:84%
And the personal
factor doesn't matter.

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:31.150 align:middle line:90%
>> Where did Eros come from?

00:04:31.150 --> 00:04:33.300 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, Eros is Cupid.

00:04:33.300 --> 00:04:38.400 align:middle line:84%
And in India, the God of love
is Kama, and he's no Cupid.

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:44.520 align:middle line:84%
He's a big, vigourous youth
with a bow and quiver of arrows.

00:04:44.520 --> 00:04:48.450 align:middle line:84%
And the names of the arrows
are such things as death

00:04:48.450 --> 00:04:54.970 align:middle line:84%
bringing, agony, and
open up, and really

00:04:54.970 --> 00:04:57.180 align:middle line:84%
he just drives
this thing into you

00:04:57.180 --> 00:05:02.010 align:middle line:84%
so that it's a total
physiological psychological

00:05:02.010 --> 00:05:05.280 align:middle line:90%
explosion that takes place.

00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:08.400 align:middle line:84%
Then the other love,
the Christian love

00:05:08.400 --> 00:05:12.630 align:middle line:84%
of agape, spiritual love, love
thy neighbor as thyself, again,

00:05:12.630 --> 00:05:15.060 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't matter
who the person is.

00:05:15.060 --> 00:05:15.940 align:middle line:90%
It's your neighbor.

00:05:15.940 --> 00:05:18.330 align:middle line:90%
You must have that kind of love.

00:05:18.330 --> 00:05:20.980 align:middle line:84%
But the kind of
seizure that comes

00:05:20.980 --> 00:05:24.570 align:middle line:84%
from the meeting of the eyes
as they say in the Troubadour

00:05:24.570 --> 00:05:30.910 align:middle line:84%
tradition, and the purely
personal person to person thing

00:05:30.910 --> 00:05:37.020 align:middle line:84%
as far as I know, it
originates as an ideal

00:05:37.020 --> 00:05:39.380 align:middle line:84%
to be lived for with
the Troubadours.

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:42.870 align:middle line:84%
>> You've said that what
happened in the 12th and 13th

00:05:42.870 --> 00:05:46.710 align:middle line:84%
centuries was one of the most
important mutations of human

00:05:46.710 --> 00:05:49.230 align:middle line:84%
feeling and spiritual
consciousness that a new way

00:05:49.230 --> 00:05:51.460 align:middle line:84%
of experiencing love
came to expression.

00:05:51.460 --> 00:05:52.260 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:56.395 align:middle line:84%
>> And it was in opposition to
that ecclesiastical despotism

00:05:56.395 --> 00:05:57.195 align:middle line:90%
of the heart--

00:05:57.195 --> 00:05:57.995 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:05:57.995 --> 00:06:02.280 align:middle line:84%
>> Which required people,
particularly young girls barely

00:06:02.280 --> 00:06:04.607 align:middle line:84%
out of adolescence to
marry whomever the church

00:06:04.607 --> 00:06:06.190 align:middle line:84%
or their parents
wanted them to marry.

00:06:06.190 --> 00:06:06.750 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:09.135 align:middle line:84%
>> And what had this done
to the passion of the heart.

00:06:09.135 --> 00:06:13.110 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, the-- to say a word
for the other before I do this,

00:06:13.110 --> 00:06:18.030 align:middle line:84%
the usual marriage in
traditional cultures is

00:06:18.030 --> 00:06:20.790 align:middle line:90%
arranged for by the families.

00:06:20.790 --> 00:06:25.660 align:middle line:84%
It's not a person to
person decision at all.

00:06:25.660 --> 00:06:30.510 align:middle line:84%
And this is true to this day
in many parts of the world.

00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:33.570 align:middle line:84%
This is not to say that
in arranged marriages

00:06:33.570 --> 00:06:35.130 align:middle line:90%
of this kind, there is no love.

00:06:35.130 --> 00:06:36.330 align:middle line:90%
There is a lot of love.

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:44.080 align:middle line:84%
There's family love and a
rich love life on that level.

00:06:44.080 --> 00:06:46.140 align:middle line:84%
So in the Middle
Ages, of course,

00:06:46.140 --> 00:06:47.730 align:middle line:84%
that was the kind
of marriage that

00:06:47.730 --> 00:06:50.430 align:middle line:90%
was sanctified by the church.

00:06:50.430 --> 00:06:56.760 align:middle line:84%
And so the idea of real
person to person marriage

00:06:56.760 --> 00:06:58.080 align:middle line:90%
was very dangerous.

00:06:58.080 --> 00:06:59.910 align:middle line:84%
>> Dangerous because
it was heresy.

00:06:59.910 --> 00:07:01.350 align:middle line:90%
>> It was not only heresy.

00:07:01.350 --> 00:07:03.120 align:middle line:90%
It was adultery.

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:06.420 align:middle line:84%
And that was
punishable by death.

00:07:06.420 --> 00:07:09.210 align:middle line:84%
For instance, in
the Tristan romance,

00:07:09.210 --> 00:07:11.670 align:middle line:90%
that's the crucial romance--

00:07:11.670 --> 00:07:12.810 align:middle line:90%
>> Tristan and Isolde?

00:07:12.810 --> 00:07:14.580 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:18.390 align:middle line:84%
Isolde was engaged
to marry King Mark.

00:07:18.390 --> 00:07:20.460 align:middle line:90%
They had never seen each other.

00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:25.770 align:middle line:84%
And Tristan is sent over
to fetch Isolde to Mark,

00:07:25.770 --> 00:07:31.320 align:middle line:84%
and Isolde's mother
prepares a love potion

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:34.860 align:middle line:84%
so that the two who
are to be married

00:07:34.860 --> 00:07:38.430 align:middle line:84%
will have real love
for each other.

00:07:38.430 --> 00:07:43.350 align:middle line:84%
And these two youngsters, they
think the love potion is wine,

00:07:43.350 --> 00:07:48.390 align:middle line:84%
and they drink it and then
are overtaken with this love.

00:07:48.390 --> 00:07:51.450 align:middle line:84%
But Brangaine, the
nurse of Isolde,

00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:53.650 align:middle line:90%
realized what had happened.

00:07:53.650 --> 00:08:00.030 align:middle line:84%
She went to Tristan and said
you have drunk your death.

00:08:00.030 --> 00:08:03.630 align:middle line:84%
And Tristan said
if by my death you

00:08:03.630 --> 00:08:09.180 align:middle line:84%
mean this agony of love that
is my life, if by my death

00:08:09.180 --> 00:08:13.110 align:middle line:84%
you mean the punishment that
we are to suffer if discovered,

00:08:13.110 --> 00:08:18.680 align:middle line:84%
which is namely
execution, I accept that.

00:08:18.680 --> 00:08:22.500 align:middle line:84%
But if by my death you
mean eternal punishment

00:08:22.500 --> 00:08:26.640 align:middle line:84%
in the fires of hell in
which these people believed,

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:30.025 align:middle line:90%
I accept that, too.

00:08:30.025 --> 00:08:31.980 align:middle line:90%
>> That was quite--

00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:33.044 align:middle line:90%
>> That's big stuff.

00:08:33.044 --> 00:08:35.755 align:middle line:84%
>> For medieval Catholic because
they believed in a literal

00:08:35.755 --> 00:08:36.555 align:middle line:90%
hell.

00:08:36.555 --> 00:08:37.638 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, these people did.

00:08:37.638 --> 00:08:38.698 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:08:38.698 --> 00:08:40.740 align:middle line:84%
So what's the significance
of what he was saying?

00:08:40.740 --> 00:08:43.890 align:middle line:84%
>> What he was saying is that
this love is bigger even than

00:08:43.890 --> 00:08:46.050 align:middle line:90%
death, than pain, than anything.

00:08:46.050 --> 00:08:51.165 align:middle line:84%
This is the affirmation of
the pain of life in a big way.

00:08:51.165 --> 00:08:56.220 align:middle line:84%
>> And I would choose this pain
for love now even though it

00:08:56.220 --> 00:09:00.160 align:middle line:84%
might mean everlasting
pain and damnation in hell.

00:09:00.160 --> 00:09:00.960 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:09:00.960 --> 00:09:03.210 align:middle line:84%
>> And that was a marked
change in how people--

00:09:03.210 --> 00:09:06.180 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, that is--

00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:10.050 align:middle line:84%
any life career that you
choose in following your bliss

00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:11.910 align:middle line:84%
should be chosen
with that sense.

00:09:11.910 --> 00:09:14.700 align:middle line:84%
Nobody can frighten me
off from this thing.

00:09:14.700 --> 00:09:18.990 align:middle line:84%
>> This is the beginning of the
Romantic idea of the Western

00:09:18.990 --> 00:09:21.937 align:middle line:84%
individual taking matters
into his or her own hand.

00:09:21.937 --> 00:09:23.250 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, absolutely.

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:27.330 align:middle line:84%
You can see there are
examples in oriental stories

00:09:27.330 --> 00:09:32.280 align:middle line:84%
of this kind of thing, but it
did not become a social system.

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:36.930 align:middle line:84%
It has now become the
ideal at any rate of love

00:09:36.930 --> 00:09:38.580 align:middle line:90%
in the Western world.

00:09:38.580 --> 00:09:40.570 align:middle line:84%
>> Love from one's
own experience?

00:09:40.570 --> 00:09:41.880 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:09:41.880 --> 00:09:44.940 align:middle line:84%
It's a very mysterious
thing, that electric thing

00:09:44.940 --> 00:09:45.990 align:middle line:90%
that happens.

00:09:45.990 --> 00:09:49.020 align:middle line:84%
And then the agony
that can follow,

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:51.900 align:middle line:84%
which is that which the
Troubadours celebrate,

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:54.780 align:middle line:84%
the agony of the love, the
sickness the doctors cannot

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:58.920 align:middle line:84%
cure, the wounds that can be
healed only by the weapon that

00:09:58.920 --> 00:09:59.850 align:middle line:90%
delivered the wound.

00:09:59.850 --> 00:10:00.900 align:middle line:90%
>> Meaning?

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:04.980 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, the wound is the wound
of my passion and agony of love

00:10:04.980 --> 00:10:08.490 align:middle line:84%
for this creature, and the only
one who can heal me is the one

00:10:08.490 --> 00:10:10.750 align:middle line:90%
who delivered the blow.

00:10:10.750 --> 00:10:15.000 align:middle line:84%
>> So we often hurt most
the person we love and heal

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.442 align:middle line:90%
the hurt by the love that hurt?

00:10:18.442 --> 00:10:20.760 align:middle line:90%
>> That's-- something like that.

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:22.670 align:middle line:90%
That's the paradox of the job.

00:10:22.670 --> 00:10:26.400 align:middle line:84%
>> What did you mean, Joe,
when you said that the triumph

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:30.510 align:middle line:84%
of Tristan's view of
love and vision of love,

00:10:30.510 --> 00:10:35.760 align:middle line:84%
this beginning of romantic love
in the West was libido over

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:38.040 align:middle line:90%
credo?

00:10:38.040 --> 00:10:41.310 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, the credo I believe--

00:10:41.310 --> 00:10:43.980 align:middle line:84%
and I believe not
only in the laws

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:47.100 align:middle line:84%
but I believe that these
laws were instituted by God

00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:50.040 align:middle line:90%
and there's no arguing with God.

00:10:50.040 --> 00:10:55.020 align:middle line:84%
These laws are just heavy weight
on me, and disobeying those

00:10:55.020 --> 00:10:55.830 align:middle line:90%
is sin.

00:10:55.830 --> 00:10:59.430 align:middle line:84%
And it has to do with
my eternal character.

00:10:59.430 --> 00:11:01.440 align:middle line:90%
>> And libido?

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:06.081 align:middle line:84%
>> Libido is the
impulse to life.

00:11:06.081 --> 00:11:08.050 align:middle line:90%
>> Comes from where?

00:11:08.050 --> 00:11:10.050 align:middle line:90%
>> Comes from the heart.

00:11:10.050 --> 00:11:11.310 align:middle line:90%
>> And the heart is what?

00:11:11.310 --> 00:11:16.320 align:middle line:84%
>> The heart is the organ of
opening up to somebody else.

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:22.020 align:middle line:84%
That's the human quality
as opposed to the animal

00:11:22.020 --> 00:11:24.300 align:middle line:84%
qualities, which
have to do with--

00:11:24.300 --> 00:11:27.420 align:middle line:90%
primarily with self-interest.

00:11:27.420 --> 00:11:30.090 align:middle line:84%
Opening up to that
which is other

00:11:30.090 --> 00:11:32.520 align:middle line:84%
is the opening of the
heart, and that's just

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:33.890 align:middle line:90%
the Troubadour's sort.

00:11:33.890 --> 00:11:35.947 align:middle line:90%
It is the opening of the heart.

00:11:35.947 --> 00:11:37.530 align:middle line:84%
>> I can certainly
understand, though,

00:11:37.530 --> 00:11:40.230 align:middle line:84%
why the church was threatened
by this because how can you have

00:11:40.230 --> 00:11:44.100 align:middle line:84%
a church if everyone's
libido is her own God?

00:11:44.100 --> 00:11:45.550 align:middle line:90%
>> Why not?

00:11:45.550 --> 00:11:49.440 align:middle line:84%
Why can't the
church handle that?

00:11:49.440 --> 00:11:54.270 align:middle line:84%
If you can sanctify a marriage
that has been arranged,

00:11:54.270 --> 00:11:55.950 align:middle line:84%
why can't you
sanctify a marriage

00:11:55.950 --> 00:11:59.280 align:middle line:84%
where two people have
joined each other?

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:04.830 align:middle line:84%
>> So the courage to love became
the courage to affirm against

00:12:04.830 --> 00:12:08.095 align:middle line:84%
tradition, whatever knowledge
stands confirmed in one's own

00:12:08.095 --> 00:12:08.895 align:middle line:90%
experience.

00:12:08.895 --> 00:12:10.485 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:12:10.485 --> 00:12:14.100 align:middle line:84%
>> Why was that important in
the evolution of the West?

00:12:14.100 --> 00:12:18.000 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, it was important in
that it gives the West this

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.320 align:middle line:84%
accent as I've been
saying on the individual,

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:26.040 align:middle line:84%
that he should have faith and
his experience and not simply

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:30.840 align:middle line:84%
mouth terms that have come
to him from other mouths.

00:12:30.840 --> 00:12:34.290 align:middle line:84%
I think that's the great thing
in the West, the validity

00:12:34.290 --> 00:12:38.310 align:middle line:84%
of the individual's
experience of what humanity

00:12:38.310 --> 00:12:41.430 align:middle line:84%
is, what life is,
what values are

00:12:41.430 --> 00:12:45.560 align:middle line:90%
against the monolithic system.

00:12:45.560 --> 00:12:49.580 align:middle line:84%
>> Was there some of this in
the legend of the Holy Grail?

00:12:49.580 --> 00:12:51.180 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:12:51.180 --> 00:12:54.420 align:middle line:84%
Wolfram has a very
interesting statement

00:12:54.420 --> 00:12:56.760 align:middle line:90%
about the origin of the Grail.

00:12:56.760 --> 00:13:01.230 align:middle line:84%
He says the Grail was
brought from heaven

00:13:01.230 --> 00:13:05.100 align:middle line:90%
by the neutral angels.

00:13:05.100 --> 00:13:10.500 align:middle line:84%
There was the war in heaven
between God and Lucifer

00:13:10.500 --> 00:13:14.550 align:middle line:84%
and the angelic hosts that
sided one group with Lucifer

00:13:14.550 --> 00:13:19.960 align:middle line:84%
and the other with
God, pair of opposites,

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:23.890 align:middle line:90%
good and evil, God and Satan.

00:13:23.890 --> 00:13:26.840 align:middle line:84%
The grail was brought
down through the middle,

00:13:26.840 --> 00:13:30.790 align:middle line:84%
the way of the middle,
by the neutral angels.

00:13:30.790 --> 00:13:32.860 align:middle line:84%
>> What is the Grail
representing then?

00:13:32.860 --> 00:13:35.300 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, the grail becomes the--

00:13:35.300 --> 00:13:37.750 align:middle line:90%
what we call it--

00:13:37.750 --> 00:13:40.150 align:middle line:84%
that which is
attained and realized

00:13:40.150 --> 00:13:44.300 align:middle line:84%
by people who have
lived their own lives.

00:13:44.300 --> 00:13:48.420 align:middle line:84%
So the story very
briefly is of this--

00:13:48.420 --> 00:13:50.420 align:middle line:84%
I'm giving it now
as Wolfram gives,

00:13:50.420 --> 00:13:53.290 align:middle line:90%
but this is just one version.

00:13:53.290 --> 00:13:55.870 align:middle line:84%
The Grail king was
a lovely young man,

00:13:55.870 --> 00:13:58.840 align:middle line:84%
but he had not
earned that position.

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:01.570 align:middle line:84%
And the Grail represents
the fulfillment

00:14:01.570 --> 00:14:04.510 align:middle line:84%
of the highest
spiritual potentialities

00:14:04.510 --> 00:14:07.150 align:middle line:90%
of the human consciousness.

00:14:07.150 --> 00:14:10.870 align:middle line:84%
And he was a lovely
young man, and he

00:14:10.870 --> 00:14:16.990 align:middle line:84%
rode forth from his castle
with the war cry amour.

00:14:16.990 --> 00:14:22.630 align:middle line:84%
And as he's riding
forth, a Muslim,

00:14:22.630 --> 00:14:26.380 align:middle line:84%
a pagan warrior, the
Mohammedan warrior,

00:14:26.380 --> 00:14:30.280 align:middle line:84%
comes out of the
woods, a knight.

00:14:30.280 --> 00:14:34.120 align:middle line:84%
And they both level their
lances at each other.

00:14:34.120 --> 00:14:39.010 align:middle line:84%
They drive at each other and
the lance of the Grail king

00:14:39.010 --> 00:14:44.200 align:middle line:84%
kills the Mohammedan but
the Mohammedan's lance

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:47.020 align:middle line:90%
castrates the Grail king.

00:14:47.020 --> 00:14:52.030 align:middle line:84%
What that means is that the
Christian separation of matter

00:14:52.030 --> 00:14:57.400 align:middle line:84%
and spirit, of the
dynamism of life

00:14:57.400 --> 00:15:01.660 align:middle line:84%
and the spiritual, natural
grace and supernatural grace

00:15:01.660 --> 00:15:04.480 align:middle line:90%
has really castrated nature.

00:15:04.480 --> 00:15:09.130 align:middle line:84%
And the European mind,
the European life,

00:15:09.130 --> 00:15:15.280 align:middle line:84%
has been as it were emasculated
by this true spirituality,

00:15:15.280 --> 00:15:18.880 align:middle line:84%
which would have come
from this has been killed.

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:21.400 align:middle line:84%
And then what did
the pagan represent?

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:24.860 align:middle line:84%
He was a person from
the suburbs of Eden.

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:28.060 align:middle line:90%
He was regarded as a nature man.

00:15:28.060 --> 00:15:35.020 align:middle line:84%
And on the head of his lance
was written the word grail.

00:15:35.020 --> 00:15:39.010 align:middle line:84%
That is to say nature
intends the grail.

00:15:39.010 --> 00:15:42.700 align:middle line:84%
Spiritual life is the
bouquet of natural life,

00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:47.060 align:middle line:84%
not a supernatural
thing imposed upon it.

00:15:47.060 --> 00:15:52.420 align:middle line:84%
And so the impulses of nature
are what give authenticity

00:15:52.420 --> 00:15:57.010 align:middle line:84%
to life, not obeying rules come
from a supernatural authority.

00:15:57.010 --> 00:15:58.795 align:middle line:90%
That's the sense of the Grail.

00:15:58.795 --> 00:16:03.550 align:middle line:84%
>> And the Grail that these
romantic legends were searching

00:16:03.550 --> 00:16:07.600 align:middle line:84%
for is the union, once again,
of what had been divided,

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:11.800 align:middle line:84%
the peace that
comes from joining?

00:16:11.800 --> 00:16:16.510 align:middle line:84%
>> The Grail becomes symbolic
of an authentic life that has

00:16:16.510 --> 00:16:21.370 align:middle line:84%
lived in terms of
its own volition,

00:16:21.370 --> 00:16:23.920 align:middle line:84%
in terms of its
own impulse system,

00:16:23.920 --> 00:16:27.640 align:middle line:84%
which carries it between the
pairs of opposites of good

00:16:27.640 --> 00:16:29.530 align:middle line:90%
and evil, light and dark.

00:16:29.530 --> 00:16:33.040 align:middle line:84%
Wolfram starts his
epic with a short poem

00:16:33.040 --> 00:16:38.780 align:middle line:84%
saying every act has both
good and evil results.

00:16:38.780 --> 00:16:44.000 align:middle line:84%
Every act in life yields pairs
of opposites in its results.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.460 align:middle line:84%
The best we can do is
lean toward the light

00:16:48.460 --> 00:16:51.850 align:middle line:90%
as they intend the light.

00:16:51.850 --> 00:16:57.160 align:middle line:84%
And what the light is that of
the harmonious relationships

00:16:57.160 --> 00:17:01.270 align:middle line:84%
that come from compassion
with suffering, understanding

00:17:01.270 --> 00:17:02.150 align:middle line:90%
of the other person.

00:17:02.150 --> 00:17:04.000 align:middle line:90%
This is what the Grail's about.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:08.410 align:middle line:84%
>> When we say God is love, does
that have anything to do with

00:17:08.410 --> 00:17:09.430 align:middle line:90%
romantic love?

00:17:09.430 --> 00:17:12.130 align:middle line:84%
Does mythology ever link
romantic love in God?

00:17:12.130 --> 00:17:14.740 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, that's what it did do.

00:17:14.740 --> 00:17:17.619 align:middle line:84%
Love was a divine
visitation, and that's

00:17:17.619 --> 00:17:20.230 align:middle line:90%
why it was superior to marriage.

00:17:20.230 --> 00:17:22.300 align:middle line:90%
That was the Troubadour idea.

00:17:22.300 --> 00:17:25.890 align:middle line:84%
If God is love, well,
then love is God.

00:17:25.890 --> 00:17:29.020 align:middle line:84%
>> There's that wonderful
passage in Corinthians by Paul

00:17:29.020 --> 00:17:31.900 align:middle line:84%
where he says love bareth all
things, endureth all things.

00:17:31.900 --> 00:17:33.340 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, that's
the same business.

00:17:33.340 --> 00:17:35.725 align:middle line:90%
Love knows no pain.

00:17:35.725 --> 00:17:39.550 align:middle line:84%
>> And yet one of my favorite
stories of mythology is out

00:17:39.550 --> 00:17:46.690 align:middle line:84%
of Persia where there's the
idea that Lucifer was condemned

00:17:46.690 --> 00:17:49.930 align:middle line:84%
to hell because he
loved God so much.

00:17:49.930 --> 00:17:56.260 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, and that's a basic
Muslim idea about Iblis--

00:17:56.260 --> 00:17:59.440 align:middle line:84%
that's the Muslim
name for Satan--

00:17:59.440 --> 00:18:02.740 align:middle line:90%
being God's greatest lover.

00:18:02.740 --> 00:18:05.410 align:middle line:84%
>> Why was Satan
thrown into hell?

00:18:05.410 --> 00:18:10.030 align:middle line:84%
Well, the standard story is that
when God created the angels,

00:18:10.030 --> 00:18:14.300 align:middle line:84%
he told them to bow
to none but himself.

00:18:14.300 --> 00:18:19.120 align:middle line:84%
Then he created man who he
regarded as a higher form

00:18:19.120 --> 00:18:23.320 align:middle line:84%
than the angels, and he asked
the angels then to serve man.

00:18:23.320 --> 00:18:27.670 align:middle line:90%
And Satan would not bow to man.

00:18:27.670 --> 00:18:30.490 align:middle line:84%
Now this is interpreted
in the Christian tradition

00:18:30.490 --> 00:18:33.400 align:middle line:84%
as I recall from my
boyhood instruction

00:18:33.400 --> 00:18:36.940 align:middle line:90%
as being the egotism of Satan.

00:18:36.940 --> 00:18:39.820 align:middle line:90%
He would not bow to man.

00:18:39.820 --> 00:18:44.440 align:middle line:84%
But in this view, he
could not bow to man

00:18:44.440 --> 00:18:46.630 align:middle line:90%
because of his love for God.

00:18:46.630 --> 00:18:49.510 align:middle line:90%
He could bow only to God.

00:18:49.510 --> 00:18:53.740 align:middle line:84%
And then God says
get out of my sight.

00:18:53.740 --> 00:18:56.470 align:middle line:84%
Now the worst of the
pains of hell in so far

00:18:56.470 --> 00:18:59.920 align:middle line:84%
as hell has been
described is the absence

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:03.610 align:middle line:90%
of the beloved, which is God.

00:19:03.610 --> 00:19:10.360 align:middle line:84%
So how does Iblis sustain
the situation in hell?

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:14.710 align:middle line:84%
By the memory of the echo
of God's voice when God said

00:19:14.710 --> 00:19:16.990 align:middle line:90%
go to hell.

00:19:16.990 --> 00:19:19.660 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's a
great sign of love.

00:19:19.660 --> 00:19:20.560 align:middle line:90%
Do you see?

00:19:20.560 --> 00:19:21.970 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's certainly
true in life

00:19:21.970 --> 00:19:26.290 align:middle line:84%
that the greatest
tale one can know

00:19:26.290 --> 00:19:28.790 align:middle line:84%
is to be separated
from the one you love.

00:19:28.790 --> 00:19:29.590 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:19:29.590 --> 00:19:33.520 align:middle line:84%
>> That's why I've like the
Persian myth for so long.

00:19:33.520 --> 00:19:34.960 align:middle line:90%
Satan is God's lover.

00:19:34.960 --> 00:19:36.070 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:19:36.070 --> 00:19:38.440 align:middle line:84%
And he is separated
from God, and that's

00:19:38.440 --> 00:19:41.830 align:middle line:90%
the real pain of Satan.

00:19:41.830 --> 00:19:46.330 align:middle line:84%
>> You once took the saying
of Jesus love your enemies

00:19:46.330 --> 00:19:49.390 align:middle line:84%
and pray for those who persecute
you so that you may be sons

00:19:49.390 --> 00:19:52.690 align:middle line:84%
of your father who's in heaven
before he makes the sun to rise

00:19:52.690 --> 00:19:54.940 align:middle line:84%
on the evil and the good
and sins reign on the just

00:19:54.940 --> 00:19:57.580 align:middle line:84%
and the unjust, you once
took that to be the highest,

00:19:57.580 --> 00:20:00.700 align:middle line:84%
the noblest, the boldest
of the Christian teachings.

00:20:00.700 --> 00:20:01.975 align:middle line:90%
Do you still feel that way?

00:20:01.975 --> 00:20:07.090 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I think the main
teaching of Christianity is

00:20:07.090 --> 00:20:08.260 align:middle line:90%
love your enemies.

00:20:08.260 --> 00:20:09.490 align:middle line:90%
>> Hard to do.

00:20:09.490 --> 00:20:11.290 align:middle line:90%
>> No, well, that's it.

00:20:11.290 --> 00:20:15.790 align:middle line:84%
When Peter drew his sword and
cut off of the servant's ear

00:20:15.790 --> 00:20:18.370 align:middle line:90%
there in the Gethsemane affair.

00:20:18.370 --> 00:20:21.340 align:middle line:84%
And Jesus said put
up your sword, Peter,

00:20:21.340 --> 00:20:23.500 align:middle line:90%
and put the ear back on.

00:20:23.500 --> 00:20:26.760 align:middle line:84%
Peter has been drawing
his sword ever since.

00:20:26.760 --> 00:20:30.640 align:middle line:84%
And one can speak about
the Petrine or Christian,

00:20:30.640 --> 00:20:35.950 align:middle line:84%
Christianity in that sense, and
I would say the main doctrine

00:20:35.950 --> 00:20:38.430 align:middle line:84%
and Christianity is
the doctrine of agape,

00:20:38.430 --> 00:20:44.300 align:middle line:84%
of a true love
for he who is here

00:20:44.300 --> 00:20:45.940 align:middle line:90%
of-- him who is your enemy.

00:20:45.940 --> 00:20:49.810 align:middle line:84%
>> How does one love one's
enemy without condoning what

00:20:49.810 --> 00:20:54.190 align:middle line:84%
the enemy does,
accepting his aggression?

00:20:54.190 --> 00:20:56.800 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I'll tell
you how to do that.

00:20:56.800 --> 00:21:01.180 align:middle line:84%
Do not pluck the moat
from your enemies' eye

00:21:01.180 --> 00:21:03.290 align:middle line:84%
but pluck the beam
from your own.

00:21:03.290 --> 00:21:04.090 align:middle line:90%
Do you know?

00:21:04.090 --> 00:21:07.350 align:middle line:90%


00:21:07.350 --> 00:21:12.420 align:middle line:84%
Now I have a friend whom I met
by chance, a young Buddhist

00:21:12.420 --> 00:21:15.765 align:middle line:90%
monk from Tibet.

00:21:15.765 --> 00:21:19.080 align:middle line:84%
In 1959, the
communists crashed down

00:21:19.080 --> 00:21:24.900 align:middle line:84%
and bombed the palace of the
Dalai Lama, bombarded Lhasa

00:21:24.900 --> 00:21:27.550 align:middle line:84%
and people murdered and
all that kind of thing.

00:21:27.550 --> 00:21:31.710 align:middle line:84%
And the escape, he escaped at
the time of the Dalai Lama.

00:21:31.710 --> 00:21:35.340 align:middle line:84%
And those monasteries,
there were monasteries

00:21:35.340 --> 00:21:39.090 align:middle line:84%
with 5,000 monks, 6,000
monks all wiped out,

00:21:39.090 --> 00:21:40.470 align:middle line:90%
tortured and everything else.

00:21:40.470 --> 00:21:47.250 align:middle line:90%


00:21:47.250 --> 00:21:52.410 align:middle line:84%
I haven't heard one word of
incrimination of the Chinese

00:21:52.410 --> 00:21:54.150 align:middle line:90%
from that young man.

00:21:54.150 --> 00:21:57.520 align:middle line:84%
There is absolutely no
condemnation of the Chinese

00:21:57.520 --> 00:21:58.320 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:21:58.320 --> 00:22:02.190 align:middle line:84%
And you hear this from
the Dalai Lama himself.

00:22:02.190 --> 00:22:04.860 align:middle line:84%
You will not hear a
word of condemnation.

00:22:04.860 --> 00:22:07.950 align:middle line:84%
This recognition
of the way of life

00:22:07.950 --> 00:22:11.670 align:middle line:84%
through which the
vitality of the Spirit

00:22:11.670 --> 00:22:15.720 align:middle line:84%
is moving in its
own way, these men

00:22:15.720 --> 00:22:19.740 align:middle line:84%
are sufferers of
terrific violence,

00:22:19.740 --> 00:22:24.940 align:middle line:90%
and there's no animosity.

00:22:24.940 --> 00:22:27.090 align:middle line:90%
I learned religion from that.

00:22:27.090 --> 00:22:31.110 align:middle line:84%
>> Do most of the stories of
mythology from whatever culture

00:22:31.110 --> 00:22:34.080 align:middle line:84%
say that suffering is
intrinsically a part of life

00:22:34.080 --> 00:22:35.655 align:middle line:84%
and that there's
no way around it?

00:22:35.655 --> 00:22:39.340 align:middle line:84%
>> I think I'd be willing
to say that they do.

00:22:39.340 --> 00:22:43.710 align:middle line:84%
I can't think of anything
now that says if you're going

00:22:43.710 --> 00:22:46.170 align:middle line:90%
to live, you won't suffer.

00:22:46.170 --> 00:22:50.350 align:middle line:84%
It'll tell you how to understand
and bear and interpret

00:22:50.350 --> 00:22:51.150 align:middle line:90%
suffering.

00:22:51.150 --> 00:22:52.780 align:middle line:90%
That it will do.

00:22:52.780 --> 00:22:56.180 align:middle line:84%
And when the Buddha says there
is escape from suffering,

00:22:56.180 --> 00:22:59.430 align:middle line:84%
the escape from
sorrow is nirvana.

00:22:59.430 --> 00:23:02.550 align:middle line:84%
Nirvana is a
psychological position

00:23:02.550 --> 00:23:09.300 align:middle line:84%
where you are untouched
by desire and fear.

00:23:09.300 --> 00:23:10.780 align:middle line:90%
>> But is that realistic?

00:23:10.780 --> 00:23:11.580 align:middle line:90%
Does that happen?

00:23:11.580 --> 00:23:13.312 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes, certainly.

00:23:13.312 --> 00:23:15.495 align:middle line:90%
>> And your life becomes what?

00:23:15.495 --> 00:23:20.550 align:middle line:84%
>> Harmonious, well-centered,
and affirmative of life.

00:23:20.550 --> 00:23:22.485 align:middle line:90%
>> Even with suffering?

00:23:22.485 --> 00:23:23.305 align:middle line:90%
>> Exactly.

00:23:23.305 --> 00:23:26.070 align:middle line:90%


00:23:26.070 --> 00:23:30.690 align:middle line:84%
There's a passage in Paul's
epistle to the Philippians,

00:23:30.690 --> 00:23:32.340 align:middle line:90%
isn't there?

00:23:32.340 --> 00:23:36.390 align:middle line:84%
Be as Christ, for Christ did
not think godhood something

00:23:36.390 --> 00:23:40.530 align:middle line:84%
to be hung on to, be
clung to but let go

00:23:40.530 --> 00:23:45.660 align:middle line:84%
and came down and took life
in the form of a servant,

00:23:45.660 --> 00:23:49.230 align:middle line:90%
a servant even unto death.

00:23:49.230 --> 00:23:58.590 align:middle line:84%
I'd say come in and accept
the suffering and affirm it.

00:23:58.590 --> 00:24:02.370 align:middle line:84%
>> So you would agree with
Abelard in the 12th century who

00:24:02.370 --> 00:24:07.110 align:middle line:84%
said that Jesus's death on the
cross was not as a ransom paid,

00:24:07.110 --> 00:24:10.860 align:middle line:84%
as a penalty applied, but it
was an act of at one-ment,

00:24:10.860 --> 00:24:14.040 align:middle line:84%
at tonement, at
one with the race.

00:24:14.040 --> 00:24:17.100 align:middle line:84%
>> That's the most sophisticated
interpretation of why Christ

00:24:17.100 --> 00:24:19.300 align:middle line:90%
had to be crucified.

00:24:19.300 --> 00:24:22.680 align:middle line:90%
Abelard's idea was that this--

00:24:22.680 --> 00:24:25.030 align:middle line:84%
oh, this is connected with
the Grail king and everything

00:24:25.030 --> 00:24:25.830 align:middle line:90%
else--

00:24:25.830 --> 00:24:30.900 align:middle line:84%
that the coming and of
Christ to be crucified

00:24:30.900 --> 00:24:34.170 align:middle line:84%
and illustrating thus
the suffering of life

00:24:34.170 --> 00:24:37.260 align:middle line:84%
removes man's mind
from commitment

00:24:37.260 --> 00:24:40.380 align:middle line:84%
to the things of this
world in compassion.

00:24:40.380 --> 00:24:44.920 align:middle line:84%
It's in compassion with
Christ that we turn to Christ.

00:24:44.920 --> 00:24:48.240 align:middle line:84%
And so the injured one
becomes the Savior.

00:24:48.240 --> 00:24:51.420 align:middle line:84%
It is the suffering
that evokes the humanity

00:24:51.420 --> 00:24:54.451 align:middle line:90%
of the human heart.

00:24:54.451 --> 00:24:58.500 align:middle line:10%
>> So you would agree with
Abelard that mankind yearning

00:24:58.500 --> 00:25:03.780 align:middle line:10%
for God and God yearning for
mankind in compassion met

00:25:03.780 --> 00:25:04.710 align:middle line:10%
at that cross?

00:25:04.710 --> 00:25:05.510 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:25:05.510 --> 00:25:07.470 align:middle line:84%
And by contemplating
the cross, you

00:25:07.470 --> 00:25:12.360 align:middle line:84%
are contemplating the
true mystery of life

00:25:12.360 --> 00:25:17.130 align:middle line:84%
and that love for this
experience, no matter

00:25:17.130 --> 00:25:21.320 align:middle line:84%
how horrific the
experience, the love for it.

00:25:21.320 --> 00:25:25.260 align:middle line:84%
>> So there's joy
and pain in love?

00:25:25.260 --> 00:25:27.030 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, there is.

00:25:27.030 --> 00:25:30.160 align:middle line:84%
Love, you might say, is
the turning point of life.

00:25:30.160 --> 00:25:32.700 align:middle line:84%
And since all life is
sorrowful, so is love.

00:25:32.700 --> 00:25:35.400 align:middle line:90%


00:25:35.400 --> 00:25:41.410 align:middle line:84%
And the stronger the love,
the more that pain but love

00:25:41.410 --> 00:25:44.170 align:middle line:90%
bears all things.

00:25:44.170 --> 00:25:47.710 align:middle line:84%
Love itself is a pain
you might say that is

00:25:47.710 --> 00:25:50.020 align:middle line:90%
the pain of being truly alive.

00:25:50.020 --> 00:25:58.272 align:middle line:90%


00:25:58.272 --> 00:26:02.280 align:middle line:84%
>> Once upon a time so long ago
it no longer matters how long

00:26:02.280 --> 00:26:05.940 align:middle line:84%
ago, the feminine figure of
the goddess ruled mythology

00:26:05.940 --> 00:26:07.890 align:middle line:90%
as the equal of the male.

00:26:07.890 --> 00:26:09.810 align:middle line:84%
The Greeks even gave
her top billing.

00:26:09.810 --> 00:26:12.390 align:middle line:84%
From chaos, they
said from nothing

00:26:12.390 --> 00:26:16.950 align:middle line:84%
came Mother Earth known
as Gaia and sky, Uranus.

00:26:16.950 --> 00:26:19.050 align:middle line:84%
They bedded, and
from their coupling

00:26:19.050 --> 00:26:21.450 align:middle line:84%
came six twins
known as the Titans

00:26:21.450 --> 00:26:24.060 align:middle line:84%
and three giants
known as Cyclopes,

00:26:24.060 --> 00:26:27.270 align:middle line:90%
each with 50 heads and 100 arms.

00:26:27.270 --> 00:26:30.840 align:middle line:84%
Uranus was disgusted and forced
him to return to their mother's

00:26:30.840 --> 00:26:33.960 align:middle line:84%
womb whereupon an
indignant Gaia set out

00:26:33.960 --> 00:26:37.110 align:middle line:84%
to make him pay for the
insult. When Uranus came

00:26:37.110 --> 00:26:39.180 align:middle line:84%
to their bedroom for
his usual favors,

00:26:39.180 --> 00:26:42.060 align:middle line:84%
she recruited one of their
sons to make a sickle,

00:26:42.060 --> 00:26:44.370 align:middle line:84%
and together they
took from Uranus

00:26:44.370 --> 00:26:46.410 align:middle line:84%
what he was most
unwilling to give up

00:26:46.410 --> 00:26:48.870 align:middle line:84%
and dropped the bloody
thing in the sea.

00:26:48.870 --> 00:26:51.210 align:middle line:84%
The lesson was not
lost on the Greeks.

00:26:51.210 --> 00:26:54.450 align:middle line:84%
It isn't nice to fool
with Mother Nature.

00:26:54.450 --> 00:26:57.240 align:middle line:84%
Joseph Campbell liked that
story and told it to me

00:26:57.240 --> 00:27:01.020 align:middle line:84%
when we were talking one day
about how patriarchal authority

00:27:01.020 --> 00:27:04.710 align:middle line:84%
finally drove the goddess from
the Pantheon of imagination.

00:27:04.710 --> 00:27:07.320 align:middle line:84%
Somehow the old guys
figured that if they wanted

00:27:07.320 --> 00:27:10.380 align:middle line:84%
to control the world, they
had to change the metaphors,

00:27:10.380 --> 00:27:12.660 align:middle line:90%
and the goddess had to go.

00:27:12.660 --> 00:27:14.910 align:middle line:84%
She remained the
symbol of fertility,

00:27:14.910 --> 00:27:19.260 align:middle line:84%
crucial to humanity's survival
but no equal except rarely

00:27:19.260 --> 00:27:21.660 align:middle line:90%
in the exercise of power.

00:27:21.660 --> 00:27:24.270 align:middle line:84%
The repercussions have
played out down the centuries

00:27:24.270 --> 00:27:25.810 align:middle line:90%
and are still with us.

00:27:25.810 --> 00:27:28.335 align:middle line:84%
We return now to
our conversation.

00:27:28.335 --> 00:27:33.060 align:middle line:84%
>> The Lord's Prayer begins
our father which art in heaven.

00:27:33.060 --> 00:27:34.040 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:27:34.040 --> 00:27:38.340 align:middle line:84%
>> Could it have
begun our mother?

00:27:38.340 --> 00:27:40.890 align:middle line:90%
>> This is a metaphorical image.

00:27:40.890 --> 00:27:43.350 align:middle line:90%
This is a symbolic image.

00:27:43.350 --> 00:27:46.680 align:middle line:84%
And to make the point that
it's not your father--

00:27:46.680 --> 00:27:51.150 align:middle line:84%
your physical father, we have
our father who art in heaven.

00:27:51.150 --> 00:27:55.950 align:middle line:84%
But heaven again is a symbolic
idea where it would heaven be.

00:27:55.950 --> 00:27:58.400 align:middle line:90%
It is no place.

00:27:58.400 --> 00:28:02.160 align:middle line:84%
All of the references of
religious and mythological

00:28:02.160 --> 00:28:05.910 align:middle line:84%
images are to planes
of consciousness

00:28:05.910 --> 00:28:10.110 align:middle line:84%
of fields of experience
potential in the human spirit.

00:28:10.110 --> 00:28:15.480 align:middle line:84%
And these are to evoke
attitudes and experiences that

00:28:15.480 --> 00:28:20.790 align:middle line:84%
are appropriate to a meditation
on the mystery of the source

00:28:20.790 --> 00:28:23.460 align:middle line:90%
of your own being I would say.

00:28:23.460 --> 00:28:27.510 align:middle line:84%
So there have been
systems of religion

00:28:27.510 --> 00:28:32.580 align:middle line:84%
where the mother is the
prime parent, the source,

00:28:32.580 --> 00:28:36.150 align:middle line:84%
and she's really a
more immediate parent

00:28:36.150 --> 00:28:39.600 align:middle line:84%
than the father because one
is born from the mother,

00:28:39.600 --> 00:28:42.810 align:middle line:84%
and then the first
experience of any infant

00:28:42.810 --> 00:28:46.740 align:middle line:84%
is the mother so that
the image of woman

00:28:46.740 --> 00:28:48.840 align:middle line:90%
is the image of the world.

00:28:48.840 --> 00:28:50.760 align:middle line:84%
You might say that
mythology is simply

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:53.940 align:middle line:84%
a translation of the
world into a mother image.

00:28:53.940 --> 00:28:56.735 align:middle line:84%
We talk of Mother
Earth and so forth.

00:28:56.735 --> 00:28:59.430 align:middle line:84%
>> But what happened
along the way, Joe,

00:28:59.430 --> 00:29:04.380 align:middle line:84%
to this reverence that in
primitive societies was

00:29:04.380 --> 00:29:07.920 align:middle line:84%
directed toward the goddess
figure, the great goddess,

00:29:07.920 --> 00:29:08.760 align:middle line:90%
the Mother Earth?

00:29:08.760 --> 00:29:09.830 align:middle line:90%
What happened to that?

00:29:09.830 --> 00:29:14.670 align:middle line:84%
>> That comes in primarily with
agriculture in the agricultural

00:29:14.670 --> 00:29:15.660 align:middle line:90%
societies.

00:29:15.660 --> 00:29:17.430 align:middle line:90%
>> Fertility and all of that?

00:29:17.430 --> 00:29:19.910 align:middle line:90%
>> It has to do with Earth.

00:29:19.910 --> 00:29:24.300 align:middle line:84%
The human woman does give
birth as the Earth gives birth

00:29:24.300 --> 00:29:26.820 align:middle line:90%
to the plants.

00:29:26.820 --> 00:29:29.880 align:middle line:84%
She gives nourishment
as the plants do.

00:29:29.880 --> 00:29:34.300 align:middle line:84%
So woman magic and Earth
magic are the same.

00:29:34.300 --> 00:29:36.030 align:middle line:90%
They are related.

00:29:36.030 --> 00:29:40.770 align:middle line:84%
And the personification
then of this energy

00:29:40.770 --> 00:29:44.290 align:middle line:84%
which gives birth to
forms and nourishes forms

00:29:44.290 --> 00:29:47.146 align:middle line:90%
is properly female.

00:29:47.146 --> 00:29:50.122 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:29:50.122 --> 00:29:51.610 align:middle line:90%


00:29:51.610 --> 00:30:00.396 align:middle line:84%
And so it is in the agricultural
world of ancient Mesopotamia,

00:30:00.396 --> 00:30:04.480 align:middle line:84%
the Egyptian Nile, but also
in the earlier planting

00:30:04.480 --> 00:30:10.370 align:middle line:84%
culture systems that the
goddess is the mythic form that

00:30:10.370 --> 00:30:11.170 align:middle line:90%
is dominant.

00:30:11.170 --> 00:30:22.300 align:middle line:90%


00:30:22.300 --> 00:30:27.300 align:middle line:84%
>> Because of this obvious
perception of creation issue--

00:30:27.300 --> 00:30:28.150 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:30:28.150 --> 00:30:33.360 align:middle line:84%
And when you have a
goddess as the creator,

00:30:33.360 --> 00:30:36.750 align:middle line:84%
it's her own very body
that is the universe.

00:30:36.750 --> 00:30:40.110 align:middle line:84%
She is identical
with the universe.

00:30:40.110 --> 00:30:43.680 align:middle line:84%
And in Egypt, you have
the mother heavens,

00:30:43.680 --> 00:30:46.560 align:middle line:84%
Nut-- the goddess Nut, who
represents the whole heavenly

00:30:46.560 --> 00:30:47.390 align:middle line:90%
sphere.

00:30:47.390 --> 00:30:53.190 align:middle line:84%
>> I was really taken when we
went to Egypt upon first seeing

00:30:53.190 --> 00:30:56.720 align:middle line:84%
the figure of Nut in the
ceiling of one of those temples.

00:30:56.720 --> 00:30:57.810 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes, I know the temple.

00:30:57.810 --> 00:30:58.830 align:middle line:90%
>> It's overwhelming.

00:30:58.830 --> 00:30:59.790 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:30:59.790 --> 00:31:02.560 align:middle line:84%
>> There's one scene of
her swallowing the sun.

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:07.830 align:middle line:84%
>> The idea is that she swallows
the sun in the West and gives

00:31:07.830 --> 00:31:11.730 align:middle line:84%
birth to the sun in the East,
and it passes through her body

00:31:11.730 --> 00:31:14.680 align:middle line:90%
at night.

00:31:14.680 --> 00:31:19.665 align:middle line:90%
And so she is the heavens.

00:31:19.665 --> 00:31:22.430 align:middle line:84%
>> So it would be natural
for people trying to explain

00:31:22.430 --> 00:31:25.520 align:middle line:84%
the wonders of the universe
to look to the female figure

00:31:25.520 --> 00:31:28.385 align:middle line:84%
as the explanation for what
they saw in their own lives.

00:31:28.385 --> 00:31:31.760 align:middle line:84%
>> Not only that but then when
you move to a philosophical

00:31:31.760 --> 00:31:37.220 align:middle line:84%
point of view, the female
represents what in the Kantian

00:31:37.220 --> 00:31:40.220 align:middle line:84%
terminology, we call the
forms of sensibility,

00:31:40.220 --> 00:31:44.990 align:middle line:84%
the female represents
time and space itself.

00:31:44.990 --> 00:31:49.850 align:middle line:84%
She is time and space,
and the mystery beyond her

00:31:49.850 --> 00:31:51.590 align:middle line:90%
is beyond pairs of opposites.

00:31:51.590 --> 00:31:53.750 align:middle line:84%
So it isn't male,
and it isn't female.

00:31:53.750 --> 00:31:57.110 align:middle line:84%
It neither is nor isn't,
but everything is within her

00:31:57.110 --> 00:32:01.670 align:middle line:84%
so that the gods
are her children.

00:32:01.670 --> 00:32:05.540 align:middle line:84%
Everything you can think
of, everything you can see

00:32:05.540 --> 00:32:09.110 align:middle line:84%
is the production
of the goddess.

00:32:09.110 --> 00:32:10.490 align:middle line:90%
Oh, there's wonderful story.

00:32:10.490 --> 00:32:16.760 align:middle line:84%
The Vedic gods are together,
and they see a strange amorphous

00:32:16.760 --> 00:32:21.110 align:middle line:84%
thing down the way
like a smoky fog.

00:32:21.110 --> 00:32:24.110 align:middle line:90%
And they say what's that.

00:32:24.110 --> 00:32:25.580 align:middle line:90%
They don't know what it is.

00:32:25.580 --> 00:32:30.800 align:middle line:84%
And Agni, the god of fire, says
I'll go find out who that is.

00:32:30.800 --> 00:32:35.090 align:middle line:84%
So he goes up to this smoky
thing, and he says who are you.

00:32:35.090 --> 00:32:39.660 align:middle line:84%
And from the smoky thing,
this voice says who are you.

00:32:39.660 --> 00:32:43.220 align:middle line:90%
And he says I'm Agni.

00:32:43.220 --> 00:32:44.420 align:middle line:90%
I'm the lord of fire.

00:32:44.420 --> 00:32:46.340 align:middle line:90%
I can burn anything.

00:32:46.340 --> 00:32:49.430 align:middle line:84%
And out of the fog there
comes a piece of straw.

00:32:49.430 --> 00:32:50.960 align:middle line:90%
It falls on the ground.

00:32:50.960 --> 00:32:53.240 align:middle line:90%
It says let's see you burn that.

00:32:53.240 --> 00:32:54.390 align:middle line:90%
He can't burn it.

00:32:54.390 --> 00:32:55.190 align:middle line:90%
He goes back.

00:32:55.190 --> 00:32:56.630 align:middle line:90%
He says this is strange.

00:32:56.630 --> 00:32:59.550 align:middle line:84%
Well, Vayu, the lord
of wind, says I'll try.

00:32:59.550 --> 00:33:01.820 align:middle line:90%
So he goes and the same thing.

00:33:01.820 --> 00:33:04.010 align:middle line:90%
I can blow anything around.

00:33:04.010 --> 00:33:04.810 align:middle line:90%
Throws it down.

00:33:04.810 --> 00:33:05.910 align:middle line:90%
Let's see you blow that.

00:33:05.910 --> 00:33:06.710 align:middle line:90%
But he can't.

00:33:06.710 --> 00:33:07.940 align:middle line:90%
He goes back.

00:33:07.940 --> 00:33:14.000 align:middle line:84%
Then a woman arrives, a
beautiful, mysterious mystic

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:15.420 align:middle line:90%
woman.

00:33:15.420 --> 00:33:20.486 align:middle line:84%
And she instructs the gods
and tells them who that is.

00:33:20.486 --> 00:33:25.700 align:middle line:84%
That is the ultimate mystery of
being from which you boys have

00:33:25.700 --> 00:33:30.470 align:middle line:84%
received your strength, and he
can turn it on or off for you.

00:33:30.470 --> 00:33:33.560 align:middle line:84%
And there she comes as the
one who illuminates the gods

00:33:33.560 --> 00:33:36.410 align:middle line:84%
themselves concerning
the ultimate ground

00:33:36.410 --> 00:33:37.835 align:middle line:90%
of their own being.

00:33:37.835 --> 00:33:40.310 align:middle line:90%
>> It's the female wisdom.

00:33:40.310 --> 00:33:43.550 align:middle line:84%
>> It's the female as
the giver of forms.

00:33:43.550 --> 00:33:45.260 align:middle line:84%
She is the one who
gave the forms,

00:33:45.260 --> 00:33:47.700 align:middle line:84%
and she knows where
they came from.

00:33:47.700 --> 00:33:50.600 align:middle line:84%
>> I wonder what it would have
meant to us if somewhere along

00:33:50.600 --> 00:33:54.570 align:middle line:84%
the way we had begun the
prayer our mother instead

00:33:54.570 --> 00:33:55.370 align:middle line:90%
of our father.

00:33:55.370 --> 00:33:58.005 align:middle line:84%
What psychological difference
would it have made?

00:33:58.005 --> 00:34:00.530 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, it makes a
psychological difference

00:34:00.530 --> 00:34:02.960 align:middle line:84%
in the character
of the cultures.

00:34:02.960 --> 00:34:05.510 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:34:05.510 --> 00:34:08.989 align:middle line:84%
You have the basic
birth of civilization

00:34:08.989 --> 00:34:11.600 align:middle line:84%
in the Near East
with the great river

00:34:11.600 --> 00:34:15.800 align:middle line:84%
valleys then as the
main source areas

00:34:15.800 --> 00:34:20.270 align:middle line:84%
the Nile, the Tigris Euphrates,
and then over in India

00:34:20.270 --> 00:34:23.690 align:middle line:84%
the Indus Valley and
later the Ganges.

00:34:23.690 --> 00:34:25.280 align:middle line:84%
This is the world
of the goddess.

00:34:25.280 --> 00:34:29.150 align:middle line:84%
All these rivers have
goddess names finally.

00:34:29.150 --> 00:34:32.060 align:middle line:90%
Then there come the invasions.

00:34:32.060 --> 00:34:35.659 align:middle line:84%
These fighting people
are hurting people.

00:34:35.659 --> 00:34:38.360 align:middle line:84%
The Semis are herders
of goats and sheep

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:41.270 align:middle line:84%
and the Indo
Europeans of cattle.

00:34:41.270 --> 00:34:43.190 align:middle line:90%
They were formerly the hunters.

00:34:43.190 --> 00:34:45.739 align:middle line:84%
They translate a
hunting mythology

00:34:45.739 --> 00:34:50.000 align:middle line:84%
into a herding mythology,
but it's animal oriented.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:53.389 align:middle line:84%
And when you have
hunters, you have killers.

00:34:53.389 --> 00:34:55.340 align:middle line:84%
And when you have
herders, you have

00:34:55.340 --> 00:34:58.100 align:middle line:84%
killers because they're
always in movement, nomadic,

00:34:58.100 --> 00:35:00.140 align:middle line:84%
coming into conflict
with other people

00:35:00.140 --> 00:35:03.920 align:middle line:84%
and they have to conquer
the area they move into.

00:35:03.920 --> 00:35:11.030 align:middle line:84%
This comes into the Near East,
and this brings in the warrior

00:35:11.030 --> 00:35:15.215 align:middle line:90%
gods like Zeus, like Yahweh.

00:35:15.215 --> 00:35:18.860 align:middle line:84%
>> The sword and death
instead of fertility?

00:35:18.860 --> 00:35:22.550 align:middle line:84%
>> Right, particularly
the Hebrews.

00:35:22.550 --> 00:35:25.820 align:middle line:84%
They really wipe
out the goddess.

00:35:25.820 --> 00:35:28.880 align:middle line:84%
The term for the goddess,
the Canaanite goddess

00:35:28.880 --> 00:35:33.920 align:middle line:84%
that's used in the Old
Testament is the abomination.

00:35:33.920 --> 00:35:37.760 align:middle line:84%
And so many of the
Hebrew kings are

00:35:37.760 --> 00:35:41.540 align:middle line:84%
condemned in the Old Testament
for having worship down

00:35:41.540 --> 00:35:42.800 align:middle line:90%
the mountaintops.

00:35:42.800 --> 00:35:45.230 align:middle line:90%
That's the goddess.

00:35:45.230 --> 00:35:49.370 align:middle line:84%
And there was a
very strong accent

00:35:49.370 --> 00:35:52.620 align:middle line:84%
against the goddess
in the Hebrew,

00:35:52.620 --> 00:35:55.730 align:middle line:84%
which you do not find
in the Indo-European.

00:35:55.730 --> 00:35:58.100 align:middle line:84%
There you have Zeus
marrying the goddess,

00:35:58.100 --> 00:36:01.250 align:middle line:90%
and then the two play together.

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:05.510 align:middle line:84%
I think it's an extreme case
that we have in the Bible,

00:36:05.510 --> 00:36:09.800 align:middle line:84%
and our own Western
subjugation of the female

00:36:09.800 --> 00:36:13.245 align:middle line:84%
is really I think a function
of biblical thinking.

00:36:13.245 --> 00:36:17.920 align:middle line:84%
>> Because when you substitute
the male for the female,

00:36:17.920 --> 00:36:21.730 align:middle line:84%
you get a different psychology,
a different cultural bias.

00:36:21.730 --> 00:36:26.890 align:middle line:84%
>> Particularly if you cut the
female out and don't have any--

00:36:26.890 --> 00:36:31.870 align:middle line:84%
if the male is on top
like this and the female

00:36:31.870 --> 00:36:34.660 align:middle line:84%
is the subordinate
all the way, you

00:36:34.660 --> 00:36:36.820 align:middle line:84%
have a totally different
system from that when

00:36:36.820 --> 00:36:38.310 align:middle line:90%
the two are facing each other.

00:36:38.310 --> 00:36:42.850 align:middle line:84%
>> And it's permissible in your
culture to do what your gods do

00:36:42.850 --> 00:36:44.060 align:middle line:90%
so you just--

00:36:44.060 --> 00:36:45.740 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, that's exactly it.

00:36:45.740 --> 00:36:49.360 align:middle line:84%
